That image came from Google Earth.  On my computer if I click on the picture it enlarges.  That is Dog Salmon creek coming down from the top of the picture and merging with the East Alsek river.  The neighbors I refer to so often live in the cabin just above mine.  That is an unused air strip behind their cabin.  Now the planes just land in front of the cabins.

Two kinds of geese were feeding in the front yard off and on during this day filled with showers.  Brant Geese and Greater White-fronted geese. The latter have beautiful coloration in their feathers.

The rain kept me inside most of the day again.  I got the cook stove tuned up and tried the oven for the first time.  I know one reader who will be pleased to read I baked a loaf of bread.  I brought 25 pounds of flour up here.  Now that I have tasted success using some of it maybe buying that much was a good idea.

The neighbor, whose cabin is just off the left side of the picture, has had a bear hanging around his place.  Tonight coming back from fishing (no luck) the bear was on the river bank in front of that same cabin.  I was maybe a hundred feet from the bear before I saw it.  One way to haze the bears and discourage them from hanging around too close is to make a lot of noise.  So not wanting to retreat and encourage the bear I down shifted and ran right at him.  He stood up to see what was causing all that noise, saw me coming at him, hollering and gunning the engine. I don't know what he thought but he went up the bank and disappeared into the brush.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

Oh boy, where to begin?  Didn’t post anything yesterday but after looking at the pictures there was plenty to write about.

Louis and I took a long walk down the river.  The wolves had preceded us.  The picture is not very good but Louis’ print is to the right of the wolf’s.  Louis is a 72 pound dog.  His print is about half the size of the wolf’s.  Two of them left new prints out front last night.

&nbsp;

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/wolftrack.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-807" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/wolftrack.jpg" alt="wolftrack" width="800" height="450" /></a>

Spring is happening now in a very big way.  It has been so warm all month.  Plants are growing several inches each day.  The yard out front has hundreds of these Shooting Stars and Wild Strawberries blooming.

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/shooting-stars.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-805" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/shooting-stars.jpg" alt="shooting stars" width="800" height="450" /></a>

&nbsp;

Kaytlynn and family stopped by last evening.  It is inspiring, this young couple making a life here in the wilderness with a three month old baby.  They are building a cabin up the creek from mine.  They let me hold baby Fathom if I have showered recently.

&nbsp;

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/withfathom.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-806" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/withfathom.jpg" alt="withfathom" width="337" height="600" /></a>

&nbsp;

Today I got the boat ready to put in the water.  It is about 5 miles to where we keep the boats out of the current in the Alsek River.

&nbsp;

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/boattrailer.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-808" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/boattrailer.jpg" alt="boattrailer" width="800" height="450" /></a>

&nbsp;

After putting the boat in the river I thought I would give her a test run.  After backing away from the shore about thirty feet she began to falter.  The engine sounded the same but she would surge then stall over and over.  I went forward and after about sixty feet the same thing happened.  Note; this is a brand new outboard I bought late last simmer for many $$.  Then I discovered the problem…I had not pulled the anchor up!

&nbsp;

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/boatinwater.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-802" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/boatinwater.jpg" alt="boatinwater" width="800" height="450" /></a>

&nbsp;

On the way back home I stopped to see if there were any fish coming in at the mouth of the East River.  The population in this part of Alaska is so small you never know when you might run into someone you know.  At the river Les, a guy we have all used as a bush pilot, had landed on the ocean beach and was fishing there in the river.  That is the Pacific Ocean in the background.  I did see one King Salmon cruse by.  It was s smallish one.  ONLY about twenty pounds!

&nbsp;

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/plane-on-beach.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-804" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/plane-on-beach.jpg" alt="plane on beach" width="800" height="450" /></a>

&nbsp;

We both caught several Dolly Varden trout.  I brought this one home and baked it for dinner.

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/dolly.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-803" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/dolly.jpg" alt="dolly" width="800" height="450" /></a>

Les flew the plane on down and visited with the neighbors.  I fished farther upstream a little longer.  Probably caught thirty Dollies, all about twenty inches long.   I didn’t season the fish at all.  I should have.  Louis liked it a lot.  I thought it was OK if I sandwiched it between saltines.

