Yesterday it was decided to finally find some way to display the antique glass fishing floats I found last year.  I thought using netting found on the beach would look cool and keep with the theme of things washed up out of the sea.  Since last summer when this idea began to develop four different nets have been considered.  The webbing in two of them was too big.  The glass floats would fall through.  The third net was a cargo net.  It was woven tight enough but the cords were so thick the floats didn't show much.  Last week I found the perfect net.  It had washed ashore and was mostly buried in the sand.

All I had to do now is find a way to modify the net to hold the floats.  The following two pictures show how I was able to keep the "sock" the same diameter so the floats stayed neat looking.  That is a four inch pipe I wrapped the net around.

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/before.jpg"><img class="wp-image-812 alignleft" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/before.jpg" alt="before" width="419" height="450" /></a><a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/after.jpg"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-811" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/after.jpg" alt="after" width="468" height="450" /></a>

Yesterday afternoon I went fishing again.  The King Salmon are back in the river.  No matter what I cast to them they would not bite.  I noted the time and tide level.  This morning at the same relative tide level I was back out there.  I fished for three hours and only caught one small flounder.  The dollies were not even biting.  So I thought I would try and find some ice for the cooler.

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/alsek-ice.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-816" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/alsek-ice.jpg" alt="alsek ice" width="800" height="450" /></a>

the cooler.  I found this eight foot long chunk on shore at the mouth of the river but the waves were breaking around it.  I didn't want or need the ice that bad so no luck fishing for ice either.

This afternoon my neighbor stopped in and said there were lots of Kings back in the river.  I blasted off down there thinking maybe I could fish a while and maybe catch more than a small flounder.  On the very first cast look what came in:

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/firstking.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-814" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/firstking.jpg" alt="firstking" width="800" height="450" /></a>

That's my size 13 insulated boot in below the fish.  It was about 40 inches long and weighed maybe 20 pounds.  I didn't have the proper license so I  returned it to the water.  These big fish put up a terrific fight.  My neighbor came down to try his luck.  Same result:

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/bentrod.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-813" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/bentrod.jpg" alt="bentrod" width="800" height="450" /></a>

Note the bent rod.    In the next hour I hooked two more Kings.  They both broke off.  One was a really big fish.  From where I hooked that second fish I had to follow it about two hundred yards down the river bank.  It was taking so much line at one point I was running to keep it from taking all the line off my reel.  It was nearly back into the ocean breakers at the mouth of the river before the line broke. Later I managed to catch this sockeye.  Louis and I will bake this guy for dinner real soon.

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/sockeye.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-815" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/sockeye.jpg" alt="sockeye" width="800" height="450" /></a>

