These posts are usually created in the evening and are an attempt to share the day.  This one is being typed around ten in the morning.  Yesterday was the first day of commercial fishing on the Alsek river.  The official opening was at twelve noon.  In preparation we had set six nets out on the shore at different "fishy" looking places.  At 12:01 yesterday we started to pull the nets out into the water.  These nets are mainly in two areas about four miles apart on the river.  Wildflower kept an eye on the three downstream.  I watched the others.  Of the six nets I was watching the one that was in the right place at the right time.  We ended up catching a bunch of Kings and several Sockeye.  Don't roll your eyes but I lost one that probably weighed 50 pounds when the gaff pulled out.  That fish was so big I was having trouble pulling it over the side of the boat when it got away.  I got home yesterday right at ten p.m. and didn't have the energy to type anything then.  Wildflower and I met again on the river at 5 this morning.  Overnight the nets did their job again.  The splash in the picture below was taken just as a King hit the net.  Note the "V" shape of the net as the fish was trying to push through.  That one weighed about 20 pounds.

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/fish-in-net.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-845" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/fish-in-net.jpg" alt="fish in net" width="800" height="450" /></a>

What a beautiful spot this was.  To be sitting out here, no sounds except a Robin singing in the trees on the opposite shore and the occasional splash of a fish in the net.  Eagles would soar silently by, hoping I would leave something for them on the shore.  They were out of luck yesterday.  All the fish were keepers.

Two nights ago I went sport fishing.  This big one did not get away.  The park ranger and a neighbor experienced with these King Salmon both said that fish would weigh close to forty pounds.  Since I caught it I'm betting it was closer to 45, maybe 50!

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/big-king.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-846" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/big-king.jpg" alt="big king" width="337" height="600" /></a>

A little while ago this morning we got word from the wildlife biologist that there were enough fish in the river to allow a second day of fishing.  Usually the first opening is for just one day.  By extending the opening until noon tomorrow means there must be a pretty good run of fish this year.  It also means another long day and short night.  I'm looking forward to a good nap tomorrow afternoon.

Almost forgot;  There was a big grizzly out front two nights ago and this morning at four, a mama and her cub were playing in the shallow water just down stream from the cabin.  I'm loving it!

