Planned today so I could be on the river at the right part of the tide for the best King fishing.  Lately that has been about three hours before low tide.  About a half mile from the place I wanted to fish I ran out of gas.  The river has several sand bars down near the mouth so I thought I would take a shortcut across the sand bars to the "prime" spot.  Well the little sloughs between the main channel and sand bars were much deeper than my boots are tall.  The half mile turned out to be somewhat farther than that.  It wasn't long before the family airplane camping came along with the Honda I let them use.  I confiscated it, came home got some gas, and now all is well again.

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Crawford-and-melinda.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-857" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Crawford-and-melinda.jpg" alt="Crawford and melinda" width="800" height="450" /></a>

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

Shortly

A good day of fishing again today.  Almost no Kings showed up in the nets but the Sockeye were plentiful and bigger than average.  This opener closes tomorrow at noon.  Wildflower and I probably won't get as big a check this week as last but we still are paying expenses with a little left over.

The weather changes here is so much different than in Colorado.  The ocean, with the cold artic currents colliding with the warmer pacific waters, cause some pretty major storms.  The moisture from the ocean doesn't have far to go here before the mountains cause the clouds to unload.  Yesterday it rained all day.  This morning the rain continued.  This afternoon the sun came out.  I was sitting in a lawn chair, out in the middle of a glacier fed river, icebergs floating by, soaking up the rays.  I'll get some pictures of that sometime soon.

It's after ten, I'm bushed, Good Night!

