A few weeks ago I might have mentioned finding a huge rope (hawser) over on the other side of the East River.  On one of the trips over there an effort was made to untangle the rope by pulling on sections of it with the Honda.  All those efforts accomplished were to make the tangles tighter and dig holes in the river bank where the Honda had spun its wheels.  Ranger Kae suggested at that time to put the rope back into the water where it would be easier to work on.  I didn’t think that was a good idea.  All I needed was some more person power.

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/kae-rope.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1060" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/kae-rope.jpg" alt="kae rope" width="448" height="252" /></a>

&nbsp;

Yesterday two of the park service men and I struck a deal.  If they would help me get the rope untangled I would lend them waders to cross the river so they could explore that remote beach along the ocean.  It was their day off so across the river we went.  Now these young men work in the maintenance division of the park.  They know how stuff works.  They spend a lot of their time clearing and maintaining the trails here at Dry Bay.  They are strong as oxen.  Energetic as young colts and smart as whips.

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/rope1.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1061" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/rope1.jpg" alt="???????????????????????????????" width="448" height="336" /></a>

&nbsp;

We fought that rope for over an hour.  One method was to find an end and work it back through the tangle.  Another method was to pull on the various loops till we could see clearly how the rats nest was formed.  Both of these approaches resulted in long lengths of very heavy rope extending out from the tangle.  The tangle was way too heavy to lift.  The idea of floating the rope reappeared.  There was quite a current in the river yesterday.  We started pulling the two loose ends and the loops into the water.  Right away the current began sweeping the rope away from us.  This turned out to be exactly what we needed to more easily pull the tangle apart.

<a href="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/rope2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1062" src="http://www.notesfromalaska.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/rope2.jpg" alt="???????????????????????????????" width="448" height="336" /></a>

&nbsp;

Now all I had to do was get the thing home.     Together we floated the rope back to my side of the river.  I hooked my Honda up to the end of the rope and started across the flat to the cabin.  After about 15 seconds of pulling on one end of the rope the Honda lost traction and buried itself in the sand.  A second Honda was needed to pull on the first one.  That didn’t work either.  Remembering Ranger Kae’s suggestion we waited for the high tide.  The rope now is doubled over in the side yard. And down the driveway...and back along the trail.  One of the men helping me measured it.  The rope is over 600 feet long.   I had designs in mind to coil the rope up in an oval like those braided rugs we have all seen and put it just outside the entrance of the cabin.  It is so big and heavy that might not work.  I’ll keep you posted.

