After striking out net fishing last night I got up early to catch the fish coming on this mornings tide.  None did.  I couldn't believe it.

The Vet came by while I was sitting on the bow of the boat waiting for a fish or four to hit the net.  He couldn't believe it either.  He already had one nice silver salmon that he caught with his fly rod.  I watched him catch another one just upstream from where I sat in the boat.  A few minutes later he was battling another one!

I pulled the boat out of the water, hurried home, grabbed my rod, jumped on the other honda and raced back up to where he was fishing.  The Vet, master angler he is, had found the elusive silver salmon.  He is such a generous person.  He had already caught his limit of four fish.  He patiently showed me where the fish were.  He gave me exact instructions on how to stand and how to hold my mouth so the fish couldn't resist the fly I was presenting.  His direction was so easy to take.  He would say "do it however you want but I have found".  My response was "now how exactly do you stand and hold your mouth that way again?".  About thirty minutes later I had my limit of four fish too.  I may not have mentioned the Vet reads these musings.  I appreciate his sharing today's fishing hot spot with me.

The wood shed is almost done.  A couple of tweeks to be sure the roof doesn't fly off this winter and I'll move on to something else.

