A couple of significant things happened since I last reported in.  The first was I remembered to wear a belt around the top of my waders when I went fishing a couple of days ago.  The belt keeps the water from filling your waders should you fall in.  The East River is mostly shallow enough that you can easily stand up should you loose your footing.  I don't usually wear the belt.  I wore it thinking it would be useful to haul the fish I had planned to catch back across from the far side of the river.  I did catch one 13 pound Silver salmon but didn't need the belt to bring that one fish across.  The place where the Vet and I were fishing has one deep hole whose sides are clay.  Slick clay.  I stepped into that hole and could not get out.  No amount of scrambling did any good.  I finally jammed the butt end of the fly rod into the edge of the hole and managed to get on my feet again.  The belt kept the water from filling the waders.  As it was they had water in them only about knee deep.

The other significant thing is the rain.  Yesterday we had over 9 inches.  This month 13.7 inches.  Since the first week of June 48.85 inches.  The rain was accompanied by a 26 mile an hour wind.

