Here we are at another McDonalds.  My breakfast is being digested and good ole Louis is waiting for his share in the truck outside.

Perfect driving weather yesterday (750 miles).  One scare though.  I was just behind the rush hour traffic in Edmonton so I went through that city without stopping.  My plan was to get to Whitehouse  then start looking for a place to stop.  As we rolled along, consuming huge amounts of fuel, I heard a "ding". The tiny gas pump on the dash was glowing and the fuel gauge needle was in the red.  It was sixty miles to Whitehouse and the truck said I had 29 miles of fuel left.  I slowed down.  I fussed at myself for leaving the rosary at home.  I started looking for friendly farmsteads where I could maybe beg for a few gallons of unleaded. Everyplace I passed looked like they only had diesel.  Cars and trucks I had zoomed past were passing me now.  Finally I saw a tiny place across the divided highway that had fuel pumps outside.  I told the lady behind the counter how happy I was to see her.

&nbsp;

I have not calculated the cost per gallon of fuel up here but it must be expensive.  It took $98.00 to fill the truck up.  The beast has a 31 gallon tank but with the big engine and carrying the camper at eighty miles an hour I am only getting about 11 miles per gallon.  I hope my accountant lets me write off part of the expense for hauling "freight" to Alaska.

