The end of April finds Louis and me at the Haines, Alaska public library where internet access available.  We got in here about eight local time last night.  The last couple of hundred miles were the most beautiful of the trip.

Since Sunday morning at ten we drove 2,780 miles averaging 62 miles an hour and gulping a gallon of fuel for every 9.5 miles traveled.  As you enter Hains you drive right by the airport.  We spent the night parked by the Mountain Flying hanger.  I will leave the truck and camper there till October.

Yesterday we drove by dozens of Bison who were grazing along the shoulder of the road.  A moose raced us along the highway for a short distance.  We saw two different black bears and a few more caribou.  The prettiest sight were the flocks of ptarmigan along the roadside. These birds are pure white in the winter for camouflage turn mottled brown for the same reason in the summer.  Some of the ones we saw were beginning to turn on their summer plumage.  As we passed them the sun was getting low.  These birds looked like snow balls lighted from within as the sun reflected off them.  There is still a lot of  snow in the mountains but as I decended back to sea level spring has returned.

Louis and I discussed how we had driven away from spring on this trip.  Back home the trees are about half way budded out.  As we came North all the deleciate, tender green of the budding trees had disappeared.  In about the last thirty miles of the trip spring came back.

The plan is to fly on over to the cabin this afternoon.  Because this is the first flight over there from Haines this year, Paul, the pilot, wanted to be sure not to arrive at the high tide.  One never knows what the winter might have done to the normal landing spots.

Last October when I took the Hughesnet antenna down I may have disturbed one of the adjustments that aligns the antenna with the sattilite.  If that is the case I may not be able to post anything else here until mid-May when some of the neighbors with undisturbed antennas show up.

If my good luck holds that won't be an issue.  Another piece of luck will be if I can get a few of the pictures I took recently to show up here:

