Yesterday afternoon we got back from doing some work at the neighbors sport fishing camp.  In another post there will be much about that.  P gave me a book to read entitled "Fishcamp" by Nancy Lord.  I started on it last night and wanted to pass on a few words Nancy wrote.  I will paraphrase some because I type so slowly but when I read the following I just wanted to pass along what I think makes me feel so connected to here.

"It wasn't long ago when living within the natural world was the rule rather than the exception, when most people were farmers, shepards and cattle drivers, loggers, cheese makers, butter churners, builders with wood and stone, fisherfolk.  Before that --- in fact, for ninety nine percent of the time humans have lived on earth --- they were hunters and gatherers.  Our ancestors knew where they fit into a world that was larger than themselves and what the connections , were between weather and food, predator and prey, wonder and cruelty.  Their understanding, though lacking the cold precision we expect today from Western science, was no less legitimate for being contained instead within elaborate sets of myths,"

She went on to say " It doesn't take much checking to recognize the extent of today's estrangement between people and nature, work and the natural environment.  For most of us today nature is what's on TV's nature programs, or it's a vacation spot , preferably sunny."

Reflectimg on Nancy Lord's words  I feel very lucky to be here this close to nature.  This close to my/our ancient roots.  A couple of times each year I close one of these posts with the following --- I'm loving it--- I really do.

