Today the population on this side of Dry Bay went from 5 people to seven.  Actually four more people arrived but two of them live on the other side of Dry Bay.  Hans, the owner/pilot of Yakutat Coastal Airlines, brought these guys in in his Otter.  He had the plane painted this last winter.  I made the mistake of being the first one to scratch it while loading a fuel drum.  He cautioned me to be more careful next time with his new $35,000 paint job.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

Some other fliers have been around for the last couple of weeks.  These geese come and go several times during the day.  They feed on the new grass coming up on the sandbars out front.  There is one snow goose hanging out with the several hundred white fronted geese.

&nbsp;

That picture is of some of the treasures I drug home from the beach.  The chain was through a hole in a log.  I think it was used to hold a raft of logs together somewhere down the coast.  It was pretty windy here today so I hung it there to serve as a wind chime.  The orange buoy attracted attention because of the macramé netting around it.  No telling how far that drifted across the pacific before washing in here.  The metal buoy has a collar around it.  It is the only one like that I have seen.  My theory is the collar makes a splashing or popping sound when the buoy is attached to the end of a net or is anchored in some way.  The noise it makes might scare the fish into a net. ???  Just a guess!

Yesterday was not a good day for the newest Honda.  When I ordered it I specified the manual pull start mechanism be added.  Figured if the battery failed while out in the bush someplace that might be handy.  Several others here have done the same.  The machine had been starting slowly so I thought I should test the manual starter.  It turns out the manual mechanism is not waterproof.  When I tested it the cord came out, the engine started but the cord would not retract….water had damaged the retracting spring.  I “fixed” (note the quotes) it and went out to gather some more logs for firewood.  Back at the cabin I shut the Honda down to unload the wood.  Went to start it…no go…grabbed the manual start cord and gave it a pull…it came out and stayed out again but the engine didn’t start.  Now it won’t start at all.  A new starter is $156.38 in Anchorage.  A new manual start mechanism is about $60.00.  One of the other fishermen told me today the going price for the few early king salmon being caught is around $9.00 a pound.  Sooo if I catch a couple of twenty pound kings early this year maybe I can get the Honda going again.

&nbsp;

Sunday, two weeks from today the first commercial fishing begins for those of us here at Dry Bay.  Some, not already occupied sawing wood, finishing cabins, moving sport camps are getting the fishing gear ready.   I pulled a couple of nets out of storage today.  If I can get to the right web sites I hope to see how to mend the torn places.

&nbsp;

There have been many eagles hanging around the beach and rivers.  They seem to know something is about to happen.  What that is I haven’t a clue but I’d bet it has to do with food.  The one below was perched on the gateway to the Vet’s cabin.  The Vet is a retired veterinarian and is a wonderful man even if his political views don’t align with mine.  Last year he noticed Louis eating a scrap of paper.  The Vet exclaimed “My God man do you realize how much money you could save by feeding him paper instead of dog food”.  He is coming back to his cabin here this week.  The Vet sent me an email asking if I needed anything.   I responded:  “Louis could use some paper to eat.  The New York Times would be OK.  Something liberal you know.”  The Vet responded:  “John:  It is reassuring to know that Lewis has the good sense to turn the Times into it;s most useful form.”…I think he probably meant dog poop.

&nbsp;

This afternoon was spent down at the mouth of the East River.  A few sockeye salmon are beginning to come in.  Didn’t catch a salmon but did snag a few Dolly Varden trout.

&nbsp;

The weather forecaster was right.  It started raining around midnight and rained steadily till about eleven then turned into a beautiful day.  The forecast for the next two days is one hundred percent chance of rain.  If it rained at night and was beautiful during the day that would be a win win for us and the forecaster.

On the way home from beach combing there were a bunch of people on the other side of the East River.  Ten hikers had come some 60 miles up the coast and were going to be picked up here at Dry Bay.  It was still cold and windy when I came across them so I offered to haul their gear back here to the cabin.  They enjoyed the warm stove and some hot tea.  Six of them were from Juneau and the others from down south.  One man and his wife upon introducing themselves self said they from Colorado.  Small world in that they live on the south side of Boulder.

The Humming birds are back!  After heating up the cabin for the hikers I left the doors open to cool things back down to normal.  Two of the tiny fliers came in to keep Louis company.  We sent them along their way unharmed.

