I'm typing this on Saturday morning.  In an hour or so Dr. Perry and I will have have another go at sewing Louis up.  The gut we had to use the first time was number 2 and had dissolved from Louis licking it so much.  Louis is now wearing a contraption made of a towel and cardboard wrapped around his neck.  We hope this will hold the incision closed so it can heal.

&nbsp;

Mike had antibiotics that Louis has been on for the last week.  There appears to be no infection.

The flight from Dry Bay to Haines went off without any hitches.  As we flew out I could see the sockeye in the East River.  Up stream a ways there was a grizzly feeding on the fish in a riffle. The big bear right in the middle of all that sparkling water was a special sight.

Today we drove all three ways out of Haines.  Two of the ways dead end in Alaska State Parks.  Both parks had really nice campgrounds.  Before we took the third way out of town we went to the SE Alaska state fair.  I was mistaken in that is another and I'm sure larger fair in Dawson a little later on.

The third way out of Haines ends at Haines Junction, Yukon.  The road between Haines and Haines Junction is the most beautiful drive I have ever been on.  In these trips up here I have crossed it in late winter (April). In the fall (October) and this time in the summer.  It is so beautiful I would be happy to meet any of you on Hains just to drive you across those hundred fifty miles.

Typing this now at the McDonalds located in the Super WalMart in Whitehorse, Yukon.  I still need to find a campground for Big Lou and myself tonight.  WalMart will let campers stay in their parking lots.  As I look outside it looks like a camper sales lot out there.  We ain't staying here.  We might just head up toward Dawson and find an old logging road, pull in there and spend a quieter night.

